2026-04-21 02:40:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 1 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 2 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 3 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 4 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 5 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 6 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 7 Indicator Holder', 'Control Module 8 Indicator Holder'] hypothesis_explanation='The indicator LEDs, which are meant to be placed in the holders on top of each control module, are physically missing. Since these indicator LEDs are installed in parallel across the switch circuit (i.e., the 12V and 0V lines in each module), their absence leaves an open circuit at the indicator position. If the circuit design is such that no current path can form (i.e., if the indicator circuit is not bypassed internally when the LED is missing), this open circuit will prevent current from flowing further along the series chain and thus also prevent the load lamp from lighting up. Since all the indicator LEDs are missing and cannot be replaced, the open circuits at each module are breaking the main circuit continuity.'
